00:17.810 --> 00:20.269
It is a beautiful day in Chicago today.

00:20.354 --> 00:22.939
Temperatures expected
to reach the upper 70s.

00:23.482 --> 00:25.400
Right now, 75 at the lakefront,

00:25.484 --> 00:28.069
74 at Midway, 73 at O'Hare.

00:28.404 --> 00:30.363
And now, up in the sky,

00:31.156 --> 00:32.990
- Don Nelson with SkyView traffic.
- Ferris?

00:33.075 --> 00:35.284
- Thanks. We've got scores of accidents.
- Ferris?

00:35.369 --> 00:36.452
Tom!

00:39.581 --> 00:41.332
- What's the matter?
- It's Ferris.

00:41.417 --> 00:43.292
- What? What's wrong?
- What's wrong? For Christ's sake

00:43.377 --> 00:45.169
look at him, honey.

00:46.505 --> 00:47.797
Ferris?

00:50.968 --> 00:54.887
He doesn't have a fever, but he says his
stomach hurts and he's seeing spots.

00:54.972 --> 00:56.848
What's the matter, Ferris?

00:57.933 --> 00:58.975
Papa?

00:59.059 --> 01:01.769
Honey, feel his hands.
They're cold and clammy.

01:06.650 --> 01:08.609
I'm fine.

01:08.694 --> 01:10.945
- I can get up.
- No.

01:11.029 --> 01:12.613
- I have a test today.
- No.

01:12.698 --> 01:14.532
You...

01:14.616 --> 01:17.160
I have to take it.

01:17.244 --> 01:20.538
I want to go to a good college,
so I can have a fruitful life.

01:20.622 --> 01:23.124
Honey, you're not going
to school like this, now.

01:23.208 --> 01:25.710
Fine. What's this? What's his problem?

01:27.254 --> 01:29.839
- He doesn't feel well.
- Yeah, right.

01:29.923 --> 01:32.008
Dry that one out,
you can fertilize the lawn.

01:32.092 --> 01:34.594
Jeanie? Is that you?

01:36.013 --> 01:38.765
Jeanie? I can't see that far.

01:39.224 --> 01:42.560
Jeanie? Jeanie, I...

01:46.023 --> 01:49.609
- Bite the big one, Junior.
- Thank you, Jeanie. You get to school.

01:49.818 --> 01:52.195
Wait, you're letting him stay home?

01:52.529 --> 01:54.614
I can't believe this.
If I was bleeding out my eyes

01:54.698 --> 01:57.283
you guys would make me go to school.
This is so unfair.

01:57.367 --> 01:59.994
Jeanie, please don't be upset with me.

02:00.162 --> 02:02.371
You have your health. Be thankful.

02:07.711 --> 02:10.253
That's it. I want out of this family.

02:12.633 --> 02:14.926
I'm okay. I'll just sleep.

02:16.428 --> 02:18.805
Maybe I'll have an aspirin around noon.

02:18.889 --> 02:21.724
Now, listen,
I'm showing some houses to that,

02:21.809 --> 02:24.143
that family from Vermont today.
So I'll be in the area.

02:24.228 --> 02:27.814
Now, my office will know just where
I am if you need me, okay?

02:28.273 --> 02:29.816
- Okay.
- Okay.

02:29.900 --> 02:31.651
I'll check on you too, pal.

02:31.735 --> 02:36.072
It's nice to know
that I have such loving, caring parents.

02:36.406 --> 02:38.783
You're both very special people.

02:43.622 --> 02:45.832
Now, you get better, pumpkin.

02:46.250 --> 02:47.959
Okay, pumpkin.

02:49.002 --> 02:50.670
I'll be home at 6:00 sharp.

02:50.754 --> 02:53.172
If you need anything, call.

02:53.257 --> 02:55.049
Ringy-dingy.

02:58.095 --> 03:01.180
- We love you, sweetie.
- I love you, too.

03:04.101 --> 03:05.935
Call if you need us.

03:14.361 --> 03:15.653
They bought it.

03:26.331 --> 03:27.456
Incredible.

03:27.541 --> 03:29.667
One of the worst performances
of my career

03:29.751 --> 03:32.128
and they never doubted it for a second.

03:37.467 --> 03:41.262
How could I possibly be expected
to handle school on a day like this?

03:51.231 --> 03:53.649
This is my ninth sick day this semester.

03:53.984 --> 03:57.153
It's getting pretty tough
coming up with new illnesses.

03:57.654 --> 04:00.740
If I go for 10, I'm probably
gonna have to barf up a lung.

04:00.824 --> 04:02.825
So I better make this one count.

04:04.995 --> 04:07.997
The key to faking out the parents
is the clammy hands.

04:08.165 --> 04:11.667
It's a good non-specific symptom.
I'm a big believer in it.

04:12.878 --> 04:16.589
A lot of people will tell you that
a good, phony fever is a dead lock.

04:16.673 --> 04:21.093
But, you get a nervous mother,
you could wind up in a doctor's office.

04:21.178 --> 04:23.179
That's worse than school.

04:24.056 --> 04:25.348
You fake a stomach cramp

04:26.016 --> 04:29.560
and when you're bent over,
moaning and wailing,

04:29.645 --> 04:31.187
you lick your palms.

04:31.271 --> 04:33.439
It's a little childish and stupid,

04:33.523 --> 04:34.941
but then, so is high school.

04:36.985 --> 04:38.611
Life moves pretty fast.

04:41.031 --> 04:44.742
If you don't stop and look around
once in a while, you could miss it.

04:47.287 --> 04:50.206
I do have a test today.
That wasn't bullshit.

04:51.208 --> 04:55.002
It's on European socialism.
I mean, really, what's the point?

04:55.087 --> 04:58.381
I'm not European.
I don't plan on being European.

04:58.507 --> 05:00.758
So, who gives a crap
if they're socialists?

05:00.842 --> 05:02.468
They could be fascist anarchists.

05:02.552 --> 05:05.721
It still wouldn't change the fact
that I don't own a car.

05:24.032 --> 05:26.117
It's not that I condone fascism

05:26.410 --> 05:28.119
or any "ism," for that matter.

05:28.203 --> 05:30.579
"Isms," in my opinion, are not good.

05:30.956 --> 05:34.667
A person should not believe in an "ism,"
he should believe in himself.

05:34.751 --> 05:39.213
I quote John Lennon, "I don't believe
in Beatles, I just believe in me."

05:39.464 --> 05:42.758
A good point there.
After all, he was "The Walrus."

05:43.510 --> 05:47.096
I could be "The Walrus."
I'd still have to bum rides off of people.

05:48.098 --> 05:49.974
- Adams?
- Here.

05:50.142 --> 05:51.934
- Adamley?
- Here.

05:52.102 --> 05:54.270
Adamowsky?

05:54.354 --> 05:56.313
- Adamson?
- Here.

05:56.440 --> 05:59.191
- Adler?
- Here.

05:59.401 --> 06:00.401
Anderson?

06:01.445 --> 06:03.529
- Anderson?
- Here.

06:04.072 --> 06:05.072
Bueller?

06:07.826 --> 06:08.826
Bueller?

06:10.328 --> 06:11.328
Bueller?

06:12.789 --> 06:15.374
- Bueller?
- He's sick.

06:16.293 --> 06:18.878
My best friend's sister's
boyfriend's brother's girlfriend

06:18.962 --> 06:21.047
heard from this guy
who knows this kid, who's going

06:21.131 --> 06:24.550
with a girl who saw Ferris pass out
at Thirty-One Flavors last night.

06:24.634 --> 06:26.427
I guess it's pretty serious.

06:27.054 --> 06:29.930
- Thank you, Simone.
- No problem whatsoever.

06:30.265 --> 06:33.601
Frye? Frye?

06:35.645 --> 06:37.188
Frye?

06:45.405 --> 06:46.655
Hello?

06:47.240 --> 06:51.160
- Cameron, babe, what's happening?
- Very little.

06:51.620 --> 06:54.997
- How do you feel?
- Shredded.

06:55.248 --> 06:57.041
Is your mother in the room?

06:58.251 --> 07:01.629
She's in Decatur.
Unfortunately, she's not staying.

07:03.673 --> 07:04.715
Where are you?

07:04.800 --> 07:07.927
I'm taking the day off.
Now get dressed and come on over.

07:08.095 --> 07:10.054
I can't, stupid, I'm sick.

07:11.181 --> 07:12.223
That's all in your head.

07:12.307 --> 07:13.432
Come on over.

07:13.850 --> 07:16.894
I feel like complete shit, Ferris.
I can't go anywhere.

07:17.145 --> 07:21.190
I'm sorry to hear that.
Now come on over here and pick me up.

07:31.493 --> 07:33.661
I'm dying.

07:38.959 --> 07:42.378
You're not dying. You just
can't think of anything good to do.

07:46.049 --> 07:48.801
If anybody needs a day off,
it's Cameron.

07:49.219 --> 07:52.721
He has a lot of things to sort out
before he graduates.

07:52.806 --> 07:54.849
He can't be wound up this tight
and go to college.

07:54.933 --> 07:56.392
His roommate will kill him.

07:56.476 --> 08:01.230
When Cameron was in Egypt's land

08:02.941 --> 08:07.153
Let my Cameron go

08:08.029 --> 08:10.531
Pardon my French,
but Cameron is so tight

08:10.740 --> 08:12.992
that if you stuck
a lump of coal up his ass,

08:13.076 --> 08:14.952
in two weeks you'd have a diamond.

08:21.668 --> 08:22.668
Katie Bueller.

08:22.752 --> 08:25.254
This is Edward R. Rooney,
Dean of Students.

08:25.422 --> 08:29.425
Oh, my God. I'm so sorry.

08:30.010 --> 08:32.303
I just completely forgot to call.

08:32.721 --> 08:35.514
Then you are aware that your son
is not in school today?

08:35.599 --> 08:37.975
Yes, I am. Ferris is home, sick.

08:38.058 --> 08:39.684
Now, I had a meeting
first thing this morning.

08:39.769 --> 08:42.438
I know I should have called,
it just completely slipped my mind.

08:42.522 --> 08:44.315
I'm really very sorry.

08:44.774 --> 08:47.026
Are you also aware, Mrs. Bueller, that

08:47.110 --> 08:49.862
Ferris does not have
what we consider to be

08:49.946 --> 08:52.031
an exemplary attendance record?

08:52.449 --> 08:53.908
I don't understand.

08:54.075 --> 08:57.036
He has missed an unacceptable number
of school days.

08:57.787 --> 08:59.205
In the opinion of this educator,

08:59.289 --> 09:02.041
Ferris is not taking
his academic growth seriously.

09:02.918 --> 09:06.587
Now, I've spent my morning
examining his records.

09:07.547 --> 09:10.799
If Ferris thinks that
he can just coast through this month

09:10.926 --> 09:13.969
and still graduate,
he is sorely mistaken.

09:14.554 --> 09:17.389
I have no reservation, whatsoever,

09:17.557 --> 09:20.476
about holding him back another year.

09:22.103 --> 09:25.481
- This is all news to me.
- Usually is.

09:26.316 --> 09:30.402
So far this semester
he has been absent nine times.

09:31.947 --> 09:35.407
- Nine times?
- Nine times.

09:35.492 --> 09:37.952
I don't remember him
being sick nine times.

09:38.036 --> 09:41.914
That's probably because he wasn't sick,
he was skipping school.

09:43.124 --> 09:45.709
Wake up and smell the coffee,
Mrs. Bueller.

09:45.835 --> 09:47.086
It's a fool's paradise.

09:47.170 --> 09:50.256
He is just leading you
down the primrose path.

09:50.340 --> 09:51.590
I can't believe it.

09:51.675 --> 09:53.968
I've got it right here in front of me.

09:54.177 --> 09:56.845
He has missed nine days.

10:05.230 --> 10:07.439
I asked for a car, I got a computer.

10:07.607 --> 10:10.109
How's that
for being born under a bad sign?

10:11.027 --> 10:12.528
Grace?

10:15.740 --> 10:17.283
Grace!

10:17.409 --> 10:20.536
Look, I can give you every assurance,
Mr. Rooney, that Ferris is home

10:20.620 --> 10:22.079
and he is very ill.

10:22.247 --> 10:24.707
In fact, I debated whether or not
I should even leave him.

10:24.791 --> 10:25.958
Grace!

10:26.042 --> 10:29.586
I can appreciate how this time of year
children are prone to taking the day off.

10:29.671 --> 10:34.550
However, in Ferris' case, I can
assure you, he is truly a very sick boy.

10:40.056 --> 10:41.557
Never had one lesson.

10:44.978 --> 10:46.312
In 1930,

10:46.396 --> 10:49.315
the Republican-controlled
House of Representatives,

10:49.399 --> 10:52.151
in an effort
to alleviate the effects of the...

10:52.485 --> 10:55.696
Anyone? Anyone?
The Great Depression,

10:56.197 --> 10:59.867
passed the... Anyone? Anyone?

11:00.452 --> 11:05.205
The tariff bill,
the Hawley-Smoot Tariff Act which...

11:06.499 --> 11:08.417
Anyone? Raised or lowered?

11:08.668 --> 11:10.544
Raised tariffs

11:10.837 --> 11:14.381
in an effort to collect more revenue
for the federal government.

11:14.966 --> 11:17.926
Did it work? Anyone?
Anyone know the effects?

11:18.678 --> 11:22.765
It did not work and the United States
sank deeper into the Great Depression.

11:23.266 --> 11:25.684
Today, we have
a similar debate over this.

11:25.769 --> 11:28.937
Anyone know what this is?
Class? Anyone?

11:29.606 --> 11:30.606
Anyone?

11:30.690 --> 11:32.358
Anyone seen this before?

11:32.609 --> 11:35.152
The Laffer Curve.
Anyone know what this says?

11:35.737 --> 11:39.990
It says, that at this point
on the revenue curve,

11:40.158 --> 11:42.993
you will get exactly
the same amount of revenue

11:43.953 --> 11:45.371
as at this point.

11:45.455 --> 11:46.872
This is very controversial.

11:46.956 --> 11:50.793
Does anyone know what Vice President
Bush called this in 1980?

11:51.086 --> 11:52.336
Anyone?

11:53.129 --> 11:55.464
Something "d-o-o" economics.

11:56.174 --> 11:57.674
Voodoo economics.

12:09.562 --> 12:10.938
Jeanie.

12:11.439 --> 12:13.232
I'm really sorry about your brother.

12:13.316 --> 12:16.151
What are you sorry for?
I have to live with the trouser snake.

12:16.236 --> 12:18.487
No, I mean, I heard he's really sick.

12:18.738 --> 12:20.823
Whoa. Whoa. Who said he's sick?

12:20.907 --> 12:24.118
A whole bunch of people. They said
he's like on the verge of death.

12:24.202 --> 12:25.994
This guy in my biology class

12:26.079 --> 12:30.332
said that if Ferris dies,
he's giving his eyes to Stevie Wonder.

12:31.042 --> 12:33.419
He's such a sweetie. Got to go.

12:34.504 --> 12:36.505
- Hi, Jeanie.
- Shut up.

12:37.924 --> 12:41.510
Please, do not yank my cord on this.
How desperate is the situation?

12:41.594 --> 12:43.345
Well, did you see Alien?

12:44.055 --> 12:46.682
When that creature
was in that guy's stomach?

12:48.017 --> 12:50.060
It kind of feels like that.

12:50.520 --> 12:51.520
Freshmen.

12:51.688 --> 12:52.938
Goddamn, are you kidding?

12:53.022 --> 12:56.275
No, of course I'm not kidding.
Do I sound like I'm kidding?

12:56.693 --> 12:57.776
Who's he talking to?

12:57.861 --> 12:59.069
Ferris Bueller, do you know him?

12:59.154 --> 13:00.863
Yeah. He's getting me
out of summer school.

13:00.947 --> 13:02.990
We appreciate you letting us know
how you're doing.

13:03.074 --> 13:04.783
We've got to buzz.
Keep a good thought, dude.

13:04.868 --> 13:05.951
Thanks.

13:07.120 --> 13:08.829
Shit. I hope he doesn't die.

13:09.164 --> 13:10.789
I can't handle summer school.

13:10.874 --> 13:14.168
- Wait a minute, give me somebody else.
- Yeah, sure, hold on.

13:15.879 --> 13:18.380
- You see Alien?
- Yeah, why?

13:21.092 --> 13:23.177
- Hello?
- Hi.

13:23.428 --> 13:25.220
Hi, Ferris, how's your bod?

13:26.431 --> 13:28.599
Oh, my God, you're dying?

13:33.062 --> 13:35.814
- Is it serious?
- I don't know. I hope not.

13:36.900 --> 13:40.027
- Think I may need a kidney transplant.
- Shit.

13:41.237 --> 13:44.448
- Are you upset?
- Excuse me.

13:44.908 --> 13:47.910
- Think you'll be alive this weekend?
- Yeah, I'd say I will.

13:47.994 --> 13:49.995
Great. Maybe I'll see you. Bye.

14:05.136 --> 14:09.932
I don't trust this kid
any further than I can throw him.

14:10.600 --> 14:13.810
Well, with your bad knee, Ed,
you shouldn't throw anybody.

14:16.189 --> 14:17.397
It's true.

14:17.982 --> 14:20.984
What is so dangerous about a character
like Ferris Bueller is

14:21.069 --> 14:23.362
he gives good kids bad ideas.

14:23.988 --> 14:26.198
The last thing I need
at this point in my career is

14:26.282 --> 14:29.826
1,500 Ferris Bueller disciples
running around these halls.

14:30.620 --> 14:34.248
He jeopardizes my ability
to effectively govern this student body.

14:34.791 --> 14:37.960
Well, makes you look like an ass
is what he does, Ed.

14:39.045 --> 14:41.380
Thank you, Grace. I think you're wrong.

14:41.464 --> 14:43.465
Well, he's very popular, Ed.

14:43.925 --> 14:46.802
The sportos and motorheads,
geeks, sluts,

14:47.053 --> 14:50.305
bloods, wasteoids,
dweebies, dickheads,

14:50.390 --> 14:51.890
they all adore him.

14:51.975 --> 14:54.059
They think he's a righteous dude.

14:56.145 --> 14:58.689
That is why
I have got to catch him this time.

14:58.982 --> 15:01.567
To show these kids
that the example he sets

15:01.651 --> 15:03.986
is a first-class ticket to nowhere.

15:05.029 --> 15:06.238
Ed.

15:06.698 --> 15:09.074
You sounded like Dirty Harry just then.

15:09.284 --> 15:10.367
Really?

15:16.916 --> 15:18.250
Thanks, Grace.

15:18.876 --> 15:20.669
I'm serious, man, this is ridiculous.

15:20.753 --> 15:22.546
Making me
wait around the house for you.

15:22.630 --> 15:24.339
Why can't you let me rot in peace?

15:24.424 --> 15:26.675
Cameron, this is my ninth sick day.

15:26.759 --> 15:28.760
If I get caught, I won't graduate.

15:28.845 --> 15:31.555
I'm not doing this for me,
I'm doing it for you.

15:31.848 --> 15:34.391
- Do you know what my diastolic is?
- Be a man.

15:34.475 --> 15:37.477
Take some Pepto-Bismol,
get dressed, and come on over here.

15:37.562 --> 15:39.980
- I'm tired of this stuff.
- Shut up.

15:40.898 --> 15:43.692
Hold your water for a second,
I got another call.

15:45.528 --> 15:47.487
- Hello?
- Ferris?

15:47.572 --> 15:48.822
Hi.

15:49.115 --> 15:50.616
You sound terrible.

15:51.200 --> 15:53.535
Really? Darn. I thought I was improving.

15:53.786 --> 15:55.203
Were you sleeping?

15:55.288 --> 15:57.873
Dad, can you hang on for a second?

15:58.249 --> 16:00.500
- Sure, pal.
- Hang on.

16:00.835 --> 16:03.545
- Cameron, it's my dad.
- Great.

16:04.088 --> 16:05.130
Keep me out of it.

16:05.214 --> 16:09.051
If you're not over here in 15 minutes,
you can find a new best friend.

16:09.594 --> 16:12.220
You've been saying that
since the fifth grade.

16:13.723 --> 16:15.432
- Dad?
- Yeah?

16:15.516 --> 16:18.393
All this talking
has made me kind of light-headed.

16:18.728 --> 16:20.562
I think I ought to lie down.

16:20.897 --> 16:24.232
Take a hot bath and then
wrap a hot towel around your head.

16:24.525 --> 16:27.361
- Wrap a hot towel around my head?
- And then

16:27.820 --> 16:30.656
make yourself some soup.
Get a nap. Okay?

16:30.740 --> 16:31.907
Okay.

16:31.991 --> 16:33.075
- Hey, Ferris?
- Yeah?

16:33.576 --> 16:35.661
- Love you, pal.
- I love you, too.

16:39.707 --> 16:41.917
I'm so disappointed in Cameron.

16:42.126 --> 16:45.671
$20 says he's sitting in his car, debating
about whether or not he should go out.

16:49.717 --> 16:51.259
He'll keep calling me.

16:51.678 --> 16:53.679
He'll keep calling me until I come over.

16:53.763 --> 16:55.681
He'll make me feel guilty.

16:56.974 --> 16:58.016
This...

16:58.101 --> 17:02.437
This is ridiculous.
Okay, I'll go, I'll go, I'll go.

17:02.522 --> 17:03.855
Shit.

17:10.154 --> 17:12.280
Goddamn it!

17:21.624 --> 17:23.500
Forget it. That's it.

17:26.921 --> 17:28.171
I'm not going.

17:43.980 --> 17:45.313
In

17:47.316 --> 17:50.318
what way

17:52.530 --> 17:55.323
does the author's use

17:55.700 --> 17:58.201
of the prison

18:02.123 --> 18:04.082
symbolize

18:13.676 --> 18:16.970
the protagonist's struggle? And

18:17.555 --> 18:19.347
how does this relate

18:19.807 --> 18:22.976
to our discussion of the uses of irony?

18:25.605 --> 18:28.648
Mr. Knowlan, may I interrupt, please?

18:35.198 --> 18:36.907
Sloane Peterson?

18:38.242 --> 18:40.368
May I have a word with you, dear?

18:42.038 --> 18:46.875
My dear, I'm afraid
that I'm the bearer of bad tidings.

18:47.543 --> 18:49.252
Your father called.

18:50.671 --> 18:52.756
Your grandmother has just passed.

18:54.967 --> 18:58.929
- No.
- Oh, darling. Oh, honey.

19:01.224 --> 19:03.058
Dead grandmother?

19:03.267 --> 19:05.560
Yes, that's what Mr. Peterson said.

19:06.020 --> 19:09.856
I had Florence Sparrow notify Sloane.
Poor little lamb.

19:10.650 --> 19:12.651
Who's this girl going out with?

19:12.944 --> 19:15.111
It's so hard to tell these days.

19:15.530 --> 19:18.406
I do see her
with Ferris Bueller quite a little bit.

19:20.409 --> 19:23.286
Would you get me
Mr. Peterson's daytime number, please?

19:23.371 --> 19:24.746
Surely.

19:27.250 --> 19:30.126
- Ed Rooney's office.
- This is George Peterson.

19:31.754 --> 19:33.088
Please hold.

19:33.172 --> 19:35.382
What do you know? It's Mr. Peterson.

19:37.093 --> 19:39.261
You still want his daytime number?

19:44.225 --> 19:47.602
- Ed Rooney.
- Ed. This is George Peterson.

19:48.271 --> 19:49.688
How are you today, sir?

19:49.772 --> 19:53.358
